05308nam a22008055i 9781503614178DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020019958  a97815036141787 a10.1515/97815036141782doi  a(DE-B1597)573868  a(OCoLC)1229161310  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aNX180.S3bC85 2021 4aNX180.S3bC85 2021 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a700.1/080944090332231 aCuillé, Tili Boon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDivining Nature :bAesthetics of Enchantment in Enlightenment France /cTili Boon Cuillé. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (350 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction The Spectacle Of Nature -- t1 The Marvels Of Nature In Buffon And Rameau -- t2 The Philosophy Of Nature In Diderot And Rousseau -- t3 The Harmony Of Nature In Paul Et Virginie -- t4 The Poetics Of Nature In Ossian And Staël -- tEpilogue A Theater Of Enchantment -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Enlightenment remains widely associated with the rise of scientific progress and the loss of religious faith, a dual tendency that is thought to have contributed to the disenchantment of the world. In her wide-ranging and richly illustrated book, Tili Boon Cuillé questions the accuracy of this narrative by investigating the fate of the marvelous in the age of reason. Exploring the affinities between the natural sciences and the fine arts, Cuillé examines the representation of natural phenomena-whether harmonious or discordant-in natural history, painting, opera, and the novel from Buffon and Rameau to Ossian and Staël. She demonstrates that philosophical, artistic, and emotional responses to the "spectacle of nature" in eighteenth-century France included wonder, enthusiasm, melancholy, and the "sentiment of divinity." These "passions of the soul," traditionally associated with religion and considered antithetical to enlightenment, were linked to the faculties of reason, imagination, and memory that structured Diderot's Encyclopédie and to contemporary theorizations of the sublime. As Cuillé reveals, the marvelous was not eradicated but instead preserved through the establishment and reform of major French cultural institutions dedicated to science, art, religion, and folklore that were designed to inform, enchant, and persuade. This book has been made possible in part by the National Endowment for the Humanities: Exploring the human endeavor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aArt and natural historyzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aArts, Frenchy18th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aEnlightenmentzFrance. 0aNatural history literaturezFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aNature in literaturexHistoryy18th century. 0aPhilosophy of naturezFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aScience and the artszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh  aEnthusiasm.  aIllusion.  aImagination.  aMarvelous.  aMelancholy.  aMemory.  aOpera.  aSpectacle of Nature.  aSublime.  aWonder.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Frontlist eBo